# PCA functions

def pca(X):
    """
    Perform Principal Component Analysis.
    
    """
    X_bar = np.mean(X, axis=0)
    X = X - X_bar
    
    cov = np.dot(X.T, X) # covariance
    eig_vals, eig_vecs = np.linalg.eig(cov)
    
    index = eig_vals.argsort()[::-1]
    eig_vals = eig_vals[index]
    eig_vecs = eig_vecs[:,index]
    
    X_new = np.matmul(X, eig_vecs)
    w = eig_vecs
    variance_explained = eig_vals / eig_vals.sum()
    
    return X_new, w, variance_explained

def plot_pca(X_new, features, w, pc_total):
    """
    Plot transformed data and features on to all vectors.
    
    """
    for i in range(pc_total-1):
        fig, ax = plt.subplots(1, 2, subplot_kw=dict(aspect='equal'),
                               gridspec_kw=dict(wspace=0.4), dpi=100)
        
        ax[0].scatter(X_new[:,i], X_new[:,i+1], marker='.', s=3, 
                      c='rebeccapurple')
        ax[0].set_xlabel('PC' + str(i+1), fontsize=10)
        ax[0].set_ylabel('PC' + str(i+2), fontsize=10)
        ax[0].set_xlim(-1.5, 1.5)
        ax[0].set_ylim(-1.5, 1.5)
        
        for spine in ['top', 'right']:
            ax[0].spines[spine].set_visible(False)
            
        for feature, vec in zip(features, w):
            ax[1].arrow(0, 0, 2.5*vec[i], 2.5*vec[i+1], width=0.01, 
                        ec='none', fc='forestgreen')
            ax[1].text(3*vec[i], 3*vec[i+1], feature, ha='center', 
                       color='rebeccapurple', fontsize=5, weight='bold')
                
        #ax[1].set_xlim(-1, 1)
        #ax[1].set_ylim(-1, 1)
        ax[1].set_xlabel('PC' + str(i+1))
        ax[1].set_ylabel('PC' + str(i+2))
        ax[1].tick_params(axis='both',which='both',top=False, bottom=False,
                          labelbottom=False, labelleft=False, left=False)
        for spine in ['top', 'right', 'left', 'bottom']:
            ax[1].spines[spine].set_visible(False)
            
def plot_boxplot_eda(df_csv, col1, col2, col3, col4, n=4):
    """
    Plot boxplots for each feature, comparing clusters.
    
    """
    order = list(range(1, n+1))

    fig, (ax1, ax2, ax3, ax4) = plt.subplots(1, 4, figsize=(12, 2), dpi=70)

    sns.boxplot(data=df_csv, x='cluster', y=col1, palette='viridis', 
                linewidth=1, ax=ax1, order=order)
    ax1.set(title=col1.title(), xlabel='Cluster', ylabel='')

    sns.boxplot(data=df_csv, x='cluster', y=col2, palette='viridis', 
                linewidth=1, ax=ax2, order=order)
    ax2.set(title=col2.title(), xlabel='Cluster', ylabel='')

    sns.boxplot(data=df_csv, x='cluster', y=col3, palette='viridis', 
                linewidth=1, ax=ax3, order=order)
    ax3.set(title=col3.title(), xlabel='Cluster', ylabel='')
    
    sns.boxplot(data=df_csv, x='cluster', y=col4, palette='viridis', 
                linewidth=1, ax=ax4, order=order)
    ax4.set(title=col4.title(), xlabel='Cluster', ylabel='')
    plt.show()

    """

    """
    fig, ax = plt.subplots()

Scouting the EPL: Player Clusters in the English Premier League¶

Executive Summary¶


With close to four billion fans around the world, football has become a worldwide phenomenon. Competition has been topnotch as leagues have been investing heavily in their players and their programs. The English Premier League is one of the top-tier leagues that boasts of having the best players in the world. Acquisitions and transfers are common in the world of football since all teams want to ramp up their chances of winning the coveted title. The quality and diversity of players have also improved in recent years, signalling better inclusion and a higher caliber of players. With the recent digital age, teams and leagues now have means to gather information on player statistics. Websites such as FBREF.com are good examples of legitimate sources of game data.

In this technical paper, our group analyzed various player and game statistics from FBREF.com. Data was extracted using manual webscraping, stored in a database, cleaned, and normalized. The data was divided into two dataframes; one for numerical statistics and the other for information like team, name, and positions. The first dataframe was used for dimensionality reduction and clustering while the latter was utilized for data exploration and analysis. Principal Component Analysis was performed to determine the correlation between features and to reduce the number of dimensions. Clustering was then executed via Ward's method of clustering. The team identified twelve new clusters; four unique clusters for each playing position. For Forwards, there are All-Around Forwards, Natural forwards, Aerial Forwards, and Defensive-Minded Forwards. For Midfielders, there are Utility Midfielders, Wide Midfielders, Holding Midfielders, and Attacking Midfielders. Finally, for Defenders, there are the Wing Backs, Full Backs, Ball-Playing Defenders, and Ball-Winning Defenders. The newly-formed clusters can be utilized by sports teams, coaches, managers, analysts, scouts, and fans for scouting, acquisitions, competition, and research.

This paper features data for players and statistics only in the 2020-2021 season of the English Premier League. We recommend future researchers to expand the scope of player statistics and go beyond the last football season. We suggest that they cover football leagues beyond the English Premier League such as the Italian Serie A, the Spanish La Liga, the FIFA World Cup, and even the Olympics. We also encourage future proponents to delve into more advanced data science techniques such as machine learning models so as to span more ground with their study and investigation. Finally, we recommend exploring other clustering methods and possibly looking into soft clusters for deeper analysis, relevant insights, and timely recommendations.

1. Introduction¶

Premier League¶


The Premier League, often referred to as the English Premier League or the EPL is the top level of the English football league system. It is contested by twenty football clubs and operates on a system of promotion and relegation with the English Football League (EFL). Seasons run from August to May with each team playing 38 matches (playing all 19 other teams both home and away). Most games are played on Saturday and Sunday afternoons. The competition was founded as the FA Premier League on February 20, 1992 following the decision of clubs in the Football League First Division to break away from the Football League and take advantage of a lucrative television rights sale. The Premier League is a corporation where chief executive Richard Masters is responsible for its management and the member clubs act as shareholders.

The Premier League is the most-watched sports league in the world, broadcasted in 212 territories to 643 million homes and a potential TV audience of 4.7 billion people. For the 2018–2019 season the average Premier League match attendance was at 38,181 while the aggregated attendance across all matches was the highest of any league at 14,508,981. Most stadium occupancies are always at near capacity. The English top-flight has produced the second-highest number of UEFA Champions League/European Cup titles, with five English clubs having won fourteen European trophies in total. Fifty clubs have competed since the inception of the Premier League in 1992, with Manchester United leading all club teams at 13 title wins.

Football Positions¶


In football, each of the 11 players on a team is assigned to a particular position on the field of play. A team is made up of one goalkeeper and ten outfield players who fill various defensive, midfield, and attacking positions depending on the formation deployed. These positions describe both the player's main role and their area of operation on the pitch.

  • Forwards (or strikers) are the players who are positioned nearest to the opposing team's goal. The primary responsibility of forwards is to score goals and to create scoring chances for other players. Forwards may also contribute defensively by harrying opposition defenders and goalkeepers while not in possession.

  • Midfielders (originally called half-backs) are players whose position of play is midway between the attacking forwards and the defenders. Their main duties are to maintain possession of the ball, taking the ball from defenders and feeding it to the strikers, as well as dispossessing opposing players. Most managers field at least one central midfielder with a marked task of breaking up opposition's attacks while the rest are more adept to creating goals or have equal responsibilities between attack and defence. Midfielders can be expected to cover many areas of a pitch, as at times they can be called back into defence or required to attack with the forwards. They are more often the players that initiate attacking plays for a team.

  • Defenders play behind the midfielders and their primary responsibility is to provide support to the team and to prevent the opposition from scoring a goal. They usually remain in the half of the field that contains the goal they are defending. Taller defenders will move forward to the opposing team's penalty box when their team takes corner kicks or free kicks, where scoring with one's head is a possibility.

  • The goalkeeper has the most defensive position in football. The goalkeeper's main job is to stop the other team from scoring by catching, palming or punching the ball from shots, headers, and crosses. Unlike their teammates, goalkeepers typically remain in and around their own penalty area for most of the game. As a result, goalkeepers have a better view of the pitch and often give advice to their defence when the other team is on the attack.

FBREF.COM¶


FBref.com is a website devoted to tracking statistics for football teams and players from around the world. FBref was created by Sports-Reference, the team behind popular statistics websites like Baseball-Reference and Basketball-Reference. They also feature American football, hockey, and college sports.

2. Problem Statement and Motivation¶


This technical report aims to unravel new and insightful player clusters based on athlete performance and on-field playing statistics in the English Premier League. Our findings will provide Football Clubs, team managers, player scouts, and game analyts with a descriptive and more in-depth analytical view of football playing positions and football players based on our discovered clusters. The insights gathered here can be utilized for player scouting, acquisition, and replacement. Scouts and managers are easily able to identify and profile players according to our clusters. Decision-makers from a particular Club or League are also able compare and analyze players from other top performing leagues for recruitment and competitive purposes. The proponents of this paper have only included players that played in the 2020-2021 season of the English Premier League.

4. Methodology¶

4.1 Data Extraction and Storage (Web Scraping)¶


Data was extracted from fbref.com through manual webscraping. Fbref.com was used to get player statistics data from the Premier League's 2020-2021 season (last season). The endpoint used was https://fbref.com/en/comps/9/10728/table_name/2020-2021-Premier-League-Stats. The website had several tables separated per players statistics category. The table_name in the endpoint pertains to the specific URL name of each table. Specific data was extracted from a total of nine tables (Table 3.1) and each was saved into a separate table in the main database epl_df.db. The player column which corresponds to the player’s name was used as the primary key of the table to uniquely identify every entry. The nine tables were eventually merged into a single FBRef table in the main database labeled as complete. The details on the code we used for scraping and merging can be found in the notebook named Supplement .

4.2 Data Cleaning, Filtering, and Normalization¶


The final tables were checked for any data that needed to be cleaned. The dual elements in the pos column were removed and the values for the mins column were converted to integer values. Goalkeeper data was not included in this report because their statistics are unique and are not applicable to other outfield players. We removed the following columns related to goalkeeper stats: cs, pksv and saves. Below is the sample table.

The data was divided into two dataframes; one for numerical stats and the other for information like name, team name, position, etc. The numerical stats dataframe was normalized using the per90 criteria. The per90 minutes criteria refers to the average number per statistic for every 90 minutes played. This aims to level the analysis between frequently and non-frequently played football players. Prior to the normalization, players with less than 90 minutes of playing time for the whole season were removed in order to eliminate the presence of outlier stats. The reasoning behind this was to remove players who did not play whole games. The raw, unfiltered data was used for the initial data exploration and analysis while the normalized per90 data was filtered by position and utilized for dimensionalty reduction and clustering.

4.3 Exploratory Data Analysis¶

  • Top Players by Stats. The complete table in the main database (epl_df) was used to create dataframes containing the top players for both offensive and defensive individual game statistics . Columns filtered for offensive statistics include player, gls, ast, sot, cmp and are equivalent to Players, Goals, Assists, Shots on Target, and Passes respectively. On the other hand, defensive statistics that include clr, int, tkl, and blocks correspond to Clearances, Interceptions, Tackles, and Blocks. These values were sorted by player and the specific game statistic in descending order. These were then plotted through individual bar graphs.

  • Statistics by Goals. For statistics on Goal points, the same data was used from the complete table. Values were grouped by Position(pos) and Age(age), the latter of which was divided into three buckets from 20-35 years of age. Both statistics were plotted against total goal points earned (gls).

  • Club Statistics. For club statistics, players were grouped into their respective squads. The same offensive and defensive statistics in the previous per player analysis were used to identify trends and to highlight which teams performed exceptionally well.

  • Positions. The Position (pos) column from the complete table was filtered to determine the distribution of playing positions among the Premier League players in the database. A bar graph was then plotted for proper visualization.

  • Nationality. The Nations (nation) column from the complete table was used to determine the various nationalities of the English Premier League football players in our database. Similarly, a bar graph was utlilized for appropriate depiction.

4.4 Dimensionality Reduction¶

Principal Component Analysis¶


Principal component analysis was implemented to analyze the correlation of the features with respect to the new dimensions formed. It was also done to reduce the size of the initial feature set to be used in select clustering methods. The team decided to perform analysis only on the per90 numerical features which are the players' in-game statistics. The data was then scaled using MinMaxScaler since the values are bound by zero. PCA was implemented and the number of principal components was determined by setting an explained variance threshold of 90%. Finally, the top four principal components were plotted against each other for dimension identification, feature correlation analysis, and top feature identification.

4.5 Clustering¶

Ward's Method¶


Ward's Linkage was used as the clustering method of choice. It is a type of hierarchical clustering where the cluster distance is measured by an increase in the sum-of-squared errors when merged. An advantage of this type of clustering is that one can easily navigate through subclusters as it is readily seen through a dendogram. In this report we tried to find the right balance between separation, composition, compactness, and the number of clusters.

Figure 5.1 Top 10 Players by Offensive Statistics for the English Premier League
The most important offensive individual player statistics that we want to highlight are Goals, Assists, Shots on Target, and Passes.

  • A goal is scored when the ball passes completely over a goal line at either end of the field of play between two centrally positioned upright goal posts. It is awarded to an offensive player who either kicks or heads the football into a goal post. This statistic is very important as the winner of a match is the team that scores more goals within a match period. In the 2020-2021 edition of the English Premier League, Harry Kane from club Tottenham Hotspur scored the most number of goals at a whopping 23 goals for the whole season, averaging almost 1 goal per match. Coming in second place and just a single goal behind the top scorer is forward Mohamed Salah from Liverpool. Manchester United's midfielder Bruno Fernandes, Leeds United's forward Patrick Bamford, and Everton's forward Dominic Calvert-Lewin occupy the rest of the top five scorers with 18, 17, and 16 goals scored respectively. The rest of the top ten scored 12-15 goals total goals each.

  • An assist is credited to a player for passing or crossing the ball to the scorer. It may also be awarded to a player whose shot rebounds either off a defender, goalkeeper or goalpost, to a teammate who scores. Some systems may credit an assist to a player who wins a penalty kick or a free kick for another player to convert, or to an attacking player for contributing to an own goal. Assists are crucial in football because it is a team sport and players are able to contribute by helping to score a goal. Similar to goals, forward Harry Kane tops the list with 14 assists in the whole season. He is followed close by Manchester United's Bruno Fernandes and Kevin de Bryune from Manchester City both with 12 assists. The rest of the top ten players for this game statistic gathered 8-11 assists.

  • A shot on target is defined as any goal attempt that goes into the net regardless of intent, and is a clear attempt to score that would have gone into the net but for being saved by the goalkeeper or is stopped by a player who is the last-man with the goalkeeper having no chance of preventing the goal. It is not to be confused with shots directly hitting the frame of the goal, unless the ball goes in and is awarded as a goal, and shots blocked by another player, who is not the last-man. Like goals and assists, Club Tottenham Hotspur's Harry Kane leads all players in the league with 47 shots on target for the whole season. Everton's Dominic Calvert-Lewin and Liverpool's Mohamed Salah, both forwards, had a total of 46 shots on target each. Ollie Watkins and Patrick Bamford complete the top 5 players with 45 each. Other players in the top 10 tallied 35 to 40 shots on target.

  • Passing the ball is a key part of football. The purpose of passing is to keep possession of the ball by maneuvering it on the ground between different players with the objective of advancing it up the playing field. Passing brings an advantage in that the team secures possession of the ball, without allowing the opposition an opportunity to attack. Andrew Robertson, a defender from Liverpool executed the most number of completed passes at 2,567. Manchester City's Rúben Dias and Rodri, Tottenham Hotspur's Pierre-Emile Højbjerg, and Liverpool's Trent Alexander-Arnold occupy the top 5 player slots with 2499, 2495 , 2389, and 2216 passes respectively. Completed passes of the rest of the top ten range from 1935 to 2117.

  • Clearance refers to the player kicking the ball away from their goal as a form of defense. A player often uses this defensive action to ensure that their opponent cannot score a goal. When performing this defensive action, it is not necessary to have an intended recipient of the ball. Tosin Adarabioyo from Fullham and Ben Mee from Burnley, both defenders, had the most number of clearances at 241. Coming close are Fullham's James Tarkowski at 236, Crystal Palace Joachim Andersen at 233, and Aston Villa's Tyrone Mings at 230. The other defenders in the top ten had 176 to 216 executed clearances

  • Interceptions occur when a member of the opposing team catches a forward pass of the ball instead of being caught by the player of the same team. Possession is then gained by the team of the opposing player who intercepted the ball. Defenders and midfielderse are usually the ones who intercept the ball. Defender Jan Benarek from Southampton had the most number of interceptions at 78. Declan Rice from West Ham United, Aaron Wan-Bissaka from Manchester United, Wilfred Ndidi from Leicester City, and N'Golo Kanté from Chelsea had 68, 66, 62, and 62 interceptions respecitvely.

  • A tackle is an act of a defender coming to meet an opponent who is in possession of the ball, engaging him, and then legally using a foot to take the ball away. This is an aggressive act that almost always involves contact, either between the players directly or with the ball between them. Tottenham Hotspur's midfielder Pierre Højbjerg executed the most number of tackles at 119. The top 5 include Luke Ayling from Leeds United with 114 tackles; Yves Bissouma from Brighton also at 114; Wilfred Ndidi from Leicester City at 108; and Aaron Wan-Bissaka from Manchester United at 97. The rest of the top ten excuted 87 to 90 tackles.

  • Blocks, simply put, are when players obstruct or prevent a shot on target from an opposing player. It is also an important defensive technique as it potentially stops the opponents from scoring goals. Manchester United's defender Aaron Wan-Bissaka led all players in blocking, garnering 113 blocks, a big stretch from the rest on the list. Everton's Ben Godfrey, Aston Villa's Tyrone Mings, Leeds United's Luke Ayling, and Aston Villa's Matt Targett, all defenders, accumulated 85, 84, 81, and 81 blocks respectively. Other players in the top ten list had 74 to 80 excecuted blocks.

We look into Goal Points by correlating it to Player Positions and Age.
  • Position. As seen in the chart displaying Goal Points versus football player positions on the left section above, forwards have the highest goal points, with an average of 5. Forwards are those who play nearest to the opposing team's goal, and are therefore most responsible for scoring goals. Their advanced position and limited defensive responsibilities mean forwards normally score more goals on behalf of their team than other players. Midfielders are more defensive-minded but are occasionally called to move further into the field to assist and score. Midfielders in the 2020-2021 season of the English Premier League average almost 2 goals. In last place are defenders that focus more on defensives skills such as blocks and interceptions. Defenders averaged almost a point each for the whole season.

  • Age. It is common in football and sports in general to assume that as athletes age, their performance slows down, affecting their individual playing statistics. There is also the concept of reaching one's peak performance at a certain age. Several studies provide some proof on the relationship between age and performance in football. The data from the 2020-2021 season of the English Premier League shows that football player ages range from as young as 20 years old to 35 years of age. The age range that scored the highest average goal points at 2.4 each is the 20-25 bracket. This is followed close by the 25-30 age bracket for football players that average around 2.2 goals. Coming in last is the 30-35 age range, averaging 1.4 goals.

5.2.1.1 Principal Component Analysis¶


To represent 90% of the explained variance, we will need 14 principal components. We will take the top features of only the top 3 PCs in our visualization.
In [19]:
# Prepare dataset for PCA
df_pca = df_fw.copy()

# Display Caption
display(HTML('<center style="font-size:12px;font-style:default;">'
             '<b> Figure 5.8 Scree Plot for Explained Variance - Forwards'
             '</b></center>'))

# Define X
X = df_pca
features = df_pca.columns

# Scaling
sscaler = MinMaxScaler()
X_norm = sscaler.fit_transform(X.astype(np.float))
X_norm_df = pd.DataFrame(data = X_norm, columns = features)
X_norm_df

X_new, w, variance_explained = pca(X_norm)

# Scree plot
fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(5,5))
ax.plot(range(1, len(variance_explained)+1), variance_explained, 'o-', 
        color='rebeccapurple', label='individual')
ax.plot(range(1, len(variance_explained)+1), variance_explained.cumsum(), 
        'o-', color='forestgreen', label='cumulative')
ax.legend()
ax.set_ylim(0, 1)
ax.set_xlabel('Principal Component')
ax.axhline(0.90, ls='--', color='r')
ax.axvline(14, ls='--', color='r')
ax.set_ylabel('Variance explained');
Figure 5.8 Scree Plot for Explained Variance - Forwards
Various interpretations can be attributed to the principal components depending on the correlated features show on on the biplots. Here are some of our takes in interpreting the top 3 principal components using the biplots and the top features:

PC1 shows top features attributted to passing and ball handling skills. Features like ball carries, ball touches, passes completed, balls recovered, and crosses are the top 5 features.

Positive PC2 dimension pertains more to offense related features like goals, penalty kicks, shots on target, and goal-creating actions. Meanwhile the negative side of the PC has mostly defense-related features including presses, tackles, interceptions, blocks, and fouls.

PC3, positive-leaning features are mostly related to playmaking. Top features found are assists and goal-creating actions. Meanwhile, for the negative side of PC3, the top features are mostly related to goal-scoring like goals, shots, and shots on target.

6. Conclusion and Recommendation¶


Our group was able to produce a total of twelve unique clusters based on three football positions (table 5.13). For Forwards, we have All-Around Forwards, Natural forwards, Aerial Forwards, and Defensive-Minded Forwards. All-Around forwards are more focused on playmaking while natural forwards are out in the field to score. Aerial forwards are also agressive in scoring but are more equipped with aerial abilities and physical types of play. Defensive-minded forwards, on the other hand, put an equal emphasis on defense and offense despite being forwards. For the Midfielder position, there are Utility Midfielders, Wide Midfielders, Holding Midfielders, and Attacking Midfielders. Utility Midfielders execute a lot of presses as well as pass interceptions and do a lot of both playmaking and defending. Wide midfielders usually play on the flanks and typically do a lot of crosses and dribbles. Holding midfielders are the most defensive-minded in the cluster, focusing on defensive actions like interceptions, ball tackles, and recoveries. Attacking midfielders, in contrast, are focused on attacking and contributing goals to the team. Finally, for Defenders, we have the Wing Backs, Full Backs, Ball-Playing Defenders, and Ball-Winning Defenders. Wingbacks, just like wide midfielders play on the flanks and are focused on attacking and scoring; they are very good at passes, crosses, and dribbles. Fullbacks, although on the defensive side, also attack and score. Ball-playing defenders are focused on defense and have many opportunites to control the ball. Ball-winning defenders are the main defenders; they excel in defensive actions such as tackles clearances and interceptions with a focus on defending their own goalpost.

To take full advantage of our formed clusters on player positions, our identified use cases are for sports teams, coaches, managers, game analyts, and scouts. Football teams, coaches, and managers are able to harness the power of these clusters to identify distributions of these types of players within their teams. With this, they can allocate resources wisely by replacing players with similar attributes once contracts expire, as well as fill in the open slots for specific players in their current roster. Scouts can use these clusters to pinpoint players from other teams or leagues for possible recruitment and player acquisitions. Furthermore, competitor's abilities can be identified from these clusters. Clubs are able to maximize their chances of winning by studying their opponent's tendencies as well as their strengths and weaknesses.

Our team recommends future proponents or researchers who have interest in this topic to delve further into football position analysis. They can start by expanding their dataset and utilize other pertinent statistics found on our source websites or other sources of information. They can take a step further and perform clustering techniques on players across different seasons of the English Premier League. Should they choose to use Ward's method for clustering, soft clusters found deeper into the dendogram can be explored to create more personalized profiles that would best fit their use case. The same methods, processes, and analysis can also be performed on additional top football leagues and football competitions such as the Spanish La Liga, the Italian Serie A, the FIFA World Cup, and the Olympics. Finally, machine learning algorithms can be utlized to predict clusters or specific player positions based on several game and player statistics.
